          "message_id": "986c0e02-15c2-4a16-9ba3-0384a52fafb2",
          "content": "Yes, exactly. The FPGA/PMOD connectors follow a standard pinout where the remaining 2 pins of each 6-pin group are **GND** and **VCC (3.3V)**. They're not signal pins so they don't appear in the constraints file at all — Vivado only needs to know about the programmable signal pins.\n\nFor a standard PMOD connector the 6-pin layout is:\n\n```\nPin 1: Signal (motor[0] or encoder[0])\nPin 2: Signal (motor[1] or encoder[1])  ← wait, that's 4 signals across upper+lower\nPin 3: GND\nPin 4: VCC (3.3V)\n```\n\nActually for the Kria's PMOD specifically, each PMOD has **12 pins total** (upper row + lower row of 6), where each row of 6 is:\n\n```\n[ sig ][ sig ][ sig ][ sig ][ GND ][ VCC ]\n```\n\nSo the 4 signal pins per motor (2 motor + 2 encoder) use 4 of those signal slots, and the remaining 2 in that row are GND and VCC — power and ground reference for the connected PCB/H-bridge circuit. That's the standard PMOD spec."
