          "content": "No, there's no separate FPGA block for steering. Here's the distinction:\n\n**In the FPGA (hardware):** All 14 motors use the identical `motor_controller` block — same PWM + H-bridge driver + quadrature decoder. The hardware doesn't know or care whether a motor is steering or driving.\n\n**In the software (C code):** There's a layered abstraction:\n\n- `MotorController` — raw MMIO wrapper, talks directly to the FPGA registers\n- `Servo` — wraps a `MotorController` + a `PIDController`. This is what makes a DC motor *behave* like a positional servo: it reads the encoder count and runs a PID loop to drive the motor to a target position.\n- `steering_motor_t` — wraps a `Servo` and adds calibration state machine logic (finding left/right/center limits) so the steering angle can be commanded in meaningful units.\n\nSo \"servo\" here doesn't mean a hobby RC servo — it means a DC motor being position-controlled via PID in software. The FPGA just provides raw PWM + encoder counting; all the closed-loop control happens on the ARM side."
