          "message_id": "819e5164-43c7-4d62-b50f-bea81fcf875f",
          "content": "An H-bridge is a circuit that lets you drive current through a motor in either direction using 4 switches arranged in the shape of the letter \"H\":\n\n```\nVCC\n |\n[S1]       [S2]\n |           |\n +---[MOTOR]-+\n |           |\n[S3]       [S4]\n |\nGND\n```\n\nTo spin **forward**, close S1 and S4 (current flows left→right through motor):\n```\nVCC\n |\n[ON ]       [OFF]\n |           \n +---[MOTOR]-+\n             |\n[OFF]       [ON ]\n             |\n            GND\n```\n\nTo spin **reverse**, close S2 and S3 (current flows right→left):\n```\nVCC\n         |\n[OFF]   [ON ]\n         |\n +---[MOTOR]-+\n |\n[ON ]   [OFF]\n |\nGND\n```\n\nThe key insight is that the motor supply voltage (could be 12V, 24V, whatever the motors need) is completely separate from the FPGA's 3.3V logic. The FPGA's two output pins just switch the transistors on/off — the H-bridge chip does the actual high-current, high-voltage work.\n\nClosing S1+S3 or S2+S4 simultaneously would short VCC directly to GND — that's a shoot-through fault and would destroy the chip. The `H_Bridge_Driver` logic in the FPGA is designed so `out1` and `out2` are never both high at the same time, which prevents this."
        }
