          "content": "The PCB schematic is a binary/compressed format — I can't read the chip name from it directly. But based on the constraints and the rest of the codebase, I can give you a definitive answer without it.\n\n---\n\nYes, the switches are transistors — specifically **MOSFETs** inside a dedicated H-bridge driver IC on the PCB. The exact chip isn't readable from the binary schematic file, but common choices for rover-scale motors are chips like the DRV8833, DRV8871, or TB6612. They all work the same way internally:\n\n```\n         VCC (motor supply, e.g. 12V)\n          |\n    ┌─────┴─────┐\n   [Q1 MOSFET] [Q2 MOSFET]   ← high-side switches (P-type or N-type with bootstrap)\n    |           |\n    +───[MOTOR]─+\n    |           |\n   [Q3 MOSFET] [Q4 MOSFET]   ← low-side switches (N-type)\n    └─────┬─────┘\n         GND\n```\n\nA MOSFET acts as a switch: apply a small voltage to its gate pin → it turns on and conducts current between its drain and source. No gate voltage → it's off. The H-bridge chip's internal logic takes your two FPGA input pins and drives the gates of all four MOSFETs appropriately, including enforcing the dead-time (a tiny delay when switching direction so Q1 and Q3 are never on simultaneously, which would short VCC to GND).\n\nSo the full chain is:\n\n```\nARM writes duty/dir → FPGA generates 3.3V logic on 2 pins → H-bridge chip gates 4 MOSFETs → motor sees full supply voltage\n```\n\nThe FPGA never touches the motor supply voltage at all — it just controls the gates."
