          "message_id": "9144951b-2583-4373-bf65-f7377f8284c0",
          "content": "The 4 pins going from the PCB to each motor are:\n\n**2 pins out → motor power**\nThese carry the actual motor supply voltage (e.g. 12V) switched by the MOSFETs. The H-bridge drives these two wires with full current — this is what actually spins the motor. By alternating which wire is high/low, direction is controlled. The PWM duty cycle is achieved by rapidly switching the MOSFETs on and off.\n\n**2 pins in → encoder**\nThese carry the quadrature encoder signals back from the motor. The encoder is a small sensor (usually optical or magnetic) built into the motor that outputs two 3.3V square waves as the shaft rotates. These go back to the FPGA pins for position counting.\n\nSo the split is: 2 wires deliver power to the motor, 2 wires read position back from it. The FPGA's `motor[0]` and `motor[1]` signals never connect to the motor directly — they only go as far as the H-bridge chip on the PCB, which then drives the actual motor wires with high current."
        }
