        "Response": {
          "message_id": "d144c717-94fb-4e44-997f-24a446fd759f",
          "content": "The Zynq UltraScale+ is the main chip on the Kria board — it's the brain of the whole system. What makes it unusual is that it's **two things in one package**:\n\n**Processing System (PS) — the ARM side**\nA quad-core ARM Cortex-A53 running at ~1.3GHz. This is a full CPU that boots Linux, runs your C rover code, handles networking, and talks to the FPGA side over an internal bus. All the PID loops, the control server, the IMU filtering (ESKF) — that all runs here.\n\n**Programmable Logic (PL) — the FPGA side**\nA sea of configurable logic gates that you program with Vivado. This is where all the Verilog you've been looking at lives — the 14 motor controllers, PWM generators, quadrature decoders, watchdog, etc. It runs at hardware speed (100MHz+), handling the timing-critical stuff that a CPU can't do reliably, like generating precise PWM signals and counting encoder pulses without missing any.\n\n**The key thing** is that the PS and PL are on the same chip and connected by a high-speed internal AXI bus. So when your C code does a memory-mapped write to a GPIO register, that signal crosses from the ARM into the FPGA fabric in nanoseconds — no external bus, no latency. That's why this architecture works well for motor control: the CPU handles the intelligence, the FPGA handles the real-time hardware interface, and they're tightly coupled.\n\nThe alternative would be a separate microcontroller talking to a separate FPGA over SPI or UART, which adds latency and complexity. The Zynq puts it all in one chip."
        }
