    "Now let me also check the block design file to understand how everything connects at the top level.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Good, I have a complete picture now. Here's a breakdown of every block type in the diagram:\n\n---\n\n## Block Diagram Overview\n\nThe design runs on a **Zynq UltraScale+ (Kria KV260)** — a chip with both an ARM processor and FPGA fabric. The PS (Processing System) side runs Linux/your C code, and the PL (Programmable Logic) side implements the motor control hardware described here.\n\n---\n\n### Zynq UltraScale+ PS (`zynq_ultra_ps_e_0`)\nThe processor itself. The ARM cores run your rover software and communicate with all the PL peripherals over the AXI bus. Everything else in the diagram is a peripheral hanging off this.\n\n---\n\n### AXI Interconnect / Crossbars (`ps8_0_axi_periph`, `xbar`, `tier2_xbar_0/1/2`)\nThese are bus routers. The PS has one AXI master port, but there are many peripherals. The crossbars fan that one connection out to all the slaves (motor controllers, GPIOs, etc.). The tiered structure (`tier2_xbar`) just means there are too many slaves for one crossbar, so they're chained.\n\n---\n\n### `motor_controller` (×14, instances 0–13)\nYour custom IP — the main workhorse. Each instance controls one motor. Internally it contains three sub-blocks:\n\n- **`control_signal_decoder`** — Takes a 15-bit control vector written by the PS over AXI and slices it into individual fields: duty cycle (8 bits), clock divisor (3 bits), direction (1 bit), H-bridge enable (1 bit), decoder clear (1 bit), decoder enable (1 bit).\n\n- **`H_Bridge_Driver` → `PWM_Generator`** — Generates a PWM signal at a frequency set by `clk_divisor` (tapping different bits of a free-running counter to divide the clock), with duty cycle set by `duty_in`. The H-bridge driver then turns that PWM + direction into two complementary signals (`out1`, `out2`) that drive the physical H-bridge chip on the PCB to spin the motor forward or backward.\n\n- **`quadDecoder` → `cntr_udclr_nb`** — Reads the two-channel quadrature encoder signals from the motor shaft. It detects which direction the encoder is moving by comparing the current and previous states of channels A and B, then increments or decrements a 16-bit counter accordingly. The PS reads this counter back to know the motor's position.\n\n---\n\n### `axi_gpio` (×15, instances 0–14)\nStandard Xilinx GPIO IP. Each one exposes a set of general-purpose I/O pins to the PS over AXI. Used here for things like servo control signals and other digital I/O that don't need the full motor controller logic.\n\n---\n\n### `watchdog`\nA safety block. It monitors a toggling signal from the PS (the PS must keep toggling it to prove it's alive). If the signal stops toggling for more than ~5ms (500,000 cycles at 100MHz), the watchdog output goes low, which disables all motor controllers (`en` input on each `motor_controller`). This prevents the rover from running away if the software crashes.\n\n---\n\n### `axi_iic_0` (I2C)\nAXI I2C controller. Used to communicate with I2C devices — most likely the IMU (BMI270) based on the rest of the codebase.\n\n---\n\n### `axi_intc_0` (Interrupt Controller)\nCollects interrupt signals from peripherals and routes them to the PS. Allows the processor to respond to hardware events (e.g., encoder overflow, I2C transaction complete) without polling.\n\n---\n\n### `clk_wiz_0` (Clock Wizard)\nTakes the raw board clock and generates the clean, phase-locked clocks needed by the PL logic (e.g., the 100MHz clock used by the watchdog and motor controllers).\n\n---\n\n### `proc_sys_reset_0/1`\nSynchronizes the reset signal from the PS to the PL clock domain, ensuring all PL logic resets cleanly when the system boots or resets.\n\n---\n\n### `auto_pc_0`\nAn auto-generated AXI protocol converter. Handles width or protocol mismatches between the PS AXI port and the PL interconnect (e.g., AXI4 ↔ AXI4-Lite conversion).\n\n---\n\n### `xlconstant_0`\nTies a signal to a constant value (likely driving the watchdog's input signal to a constant during testing, or tying off unused ports).\n\n---\n\n**In summary**, the data flow is: PS writes a control vector → AXI crossbar routes it → `motor_controller` decodes it → PWM drives the H-bridge → motor spins. Meanwhile the encoder feeds back into the `quadDecoder` → PS reads position. The watchdog sits across all of this as a safety kill switch.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> can you explain the motor controllers in more depth please",
    "Sure. Let me re-read the relevant files to give you precise details.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Here's a deep dive into the motor controller.\n\n---\n\n## The Control Vector — the interface to software\n\nEverything starts with a single 15-bit word the PS writes over AXI. The `control_signal_decoder` just slices it up with `assign` statements — pure combinational wiring, no logic:\n\n```\nBit(s)  Field           Width   Purpose\n------  -----           -----   -------\n[7:0]   motor_duty_in   8 bits  PWM duty cycle (0–255)\n[10:8]  clk_divisor     3 bits  PWM frequency selector\n[11]    motor_dir       1 bit   Spin direction\n[12]    h_bridge_en     1 bit   Enable the H-bridge\n[13]    dec_clr         1 bit   Reset the position counter to 0\n[14]    dec_en          1 bit   Enable position counting\n```\n\nSo to spin a motor forward at 50% speed, you'd write `0b_01_1_0_100_10000000` (h_bridge_en=1, dir=0, clk_divisor=4, duty=128).\n\n---\n\n## PWM Generator — how speed is controlled\n\nThe PWM frequency is set by tapping a bit from a free-running 16-bit counter:\n\n```verilog\nassign clk_div = clk_cntr[clk_divisor];\n```\n\nBit 0 of the counter toggles every clock cycle (100MHz → 50MHz), bit 1 every 2 cycles (25MHz), ..., bit N divides by 2^(N+1). So `clk_divisor` gives you 8 possible PWM carrier frequencies ranging from ~50MHz down to ~390kHz. You pick whichever suits your motor.\n\nThe duty cycle works by counting 0–255 on `pwm_cntr` (clocked by `clk_div`) and comparing against `pwm_duty`:\n\n```verilog\nPWM_OUT <= (pwm_cntr < pwm_duty);\n```\n\nSo `duty=0` → always off, `duty=128` → 50%, `duty=255` → ~100%. The resolution is 8 bits (256 steps).\n\n---\n\n## H-Bridge Driver — how direction is controlled\n\nAn H-bridge needs two control signals. Driving `out1` high and `out2` low spins one way; flipping them spins the other. The logic is:\n\n```verilog\nassign out1 = ((~pwm) | dir) & en;\nassign out2 = ~(pwm & dir) & en;\n```\n\nWorking through the two cases:\n\n- **dir=0 (forward):** `out1 = ~pwm`, `out2 = 1`. The PWM signal appears on `out1` inverted, `out2` is held high — the motor sees a pulsed voltage in one direction.\n- **dir=1 (reverse):** `out1 = 1`, `out2 = ~pwm`. Now `out2` carries the inverted PWM, `out1` is held high — motor spins the other way.\n\nBoth outputs go low when `en=0` (either `h_bridge_en` in the control vector is 0, or the watchdog killed it).\n\n---\n\n## Quadrature Decoder — how position is measured\n\nQuadrature encoders output two square waves (A and B) 90° out of phase. The direction of motion determines which one leads the other.\n\nThe decoder registers A and B, then also keeps one-cycle-delayed copies (`A_FF`, `B_FF`). Note the encoder signals are active-low on this hardware, so they're inverted first:\n\n```verilog\nA <= ~enc_a;\nB <= ~enc_b;\n```\n\nDirection detection:\n```verilog\ncounter_up   = A ^ B_FF;   // A just changed while B was stable → moving forward\ncounter_down = B ^ A_FF;   // B just changed while A was stable → moving backward\n```\n\n`counter_en` fires only when exactly one of those is true (XOR), meaning the encoder actually moved. This prevents double-counting on noisy edges.\n\nThe result feeds into `cntr_udclr_nb`, a generic 16-bit up/down counter. It increments on `counter_up`, decrements on `counter_down`, and resets to 0 asynchronously when `dec_clr` is pulsed. The PS reads the 16-bit `motor_pos` output to know where the motor shaft is.\n\nThe 16-bit range gives you ±32,767 counts from the zero point (or 0–65,535 if you treat it as unsigned) before it wraps.\n\n---\n\n## Enable gating — the safety interlock\n\nThe H-bridge enable has a two-input AND:\n\n```verilog\n.en (h_bridge_en && en)\n```\n\n`h_bridge_en` comes from the control vector (software control), `en` comes from the watchdog. **Both must be high** for the motor to run. The watchdog can cut power to all 14 motors simultaneously regardless of what the software wrote into the control registers.\n[Tool uses: none]",
