    "Now I have the complete picture. Here's the full answer:\n\n---\n\n## Inputs to `motor_controller`\n\n**`control_vector_in` — from `axi_gpio_motorN/gpio_io_o`**\n\nEach motor controller is paired with a dedicated `axi_gpio` block configured as a **dual-channel GPIO**:\n- Channel 1 (`gpio_io_o`): 15-bit **output** — the PS writes the control vector here, and it wires directly to `control_vector_in`.\n- Channel 2 (`gpio2_io_i`): 16-bit **input** — reads `motor_pos` back.\n\nSo the full software flow is: your C code does a memory-mapped write to the GPIO's output register → the 15-bit value appears on `gpio_io_o` → feeds straight into `control_vector_in`. No interrupt, no DMA — just a register write.\n\n**`enc_in[1:0]` — from FPGA pins (`encoder0`–`encoder13`)**\n\nThe two quadrature encoder signals come directly from physical I/O pins on the Kria, routed through the constraints file to wherever the encoder is physically wired on the PCB.\n\n**`en` — from `watchdog_0/watchdog_out`**\n\nA single watchdog output fans out to **all 14** motor controllers simultaneously. It also drives `user_led1` as a visual indicator that the watchdog is alive.\n\n---\n\n## Outputs from `motor_controller`\n\n**`h_bridge_cntrl[1:0]` → FPGA pins (`motor0`–`motor13`)**\n\nThe two H-bridge control signals go directly out to physical FPGA pins, which connect to the H-bridge chips on the PCB that actually drive the motors.\n\n**`motor_pos[15:0]` → `axi_gpio_motorN/gpio2_io_i`**\n\nThe 16-bit position counter feeds back into channel 2 of the same GPIO block that sent the control vector. Your C code reads it with a memory-mapped read from that GPIO's input register.\n\n---\n\n## Summary diagram for one motor\n\n```\nPS (C code)\n    │ mmio write\n    ▼\naxi_gpio_motorN\n    │ gpio_io_o [14:0]          gpio2_io_i [15:0] ▲\n    ▼                                              │\nmotor_controller_N ──────────────────────────── motor_pos\n    │ control_vector_in                            │\n    │                                              │\n    │ enc_in ◄── encoder pins (physical)           │\n    │                                              │\n    │ en ◄── watchdog_out                          │\n    │                                              │\n    └── h_bridge_cntrl ──► motor pins (physical)   │\n                                                   │\n                           quadDecoder ────────────┘\n```\n\nThe `axi_gpio` block is doing double duty as both the command register (write channel 1) and the status register (read channel 2) for each motor.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> how do these inputs and outputs relate to the 6 pins that actually connect from the board to the physical motors",
    "Let me check the constraints file which maps FPGA pins to board signals.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now the full picture is clear. Here's how it all maps together:\n\n---\n\n## The 4 physical pins per motor\n\nEach motor uses exactly **4 pins** on the FPGA connector (not 6 — the constraints show 2 motor + 2 encoder per motor):\n\n| Pin | Signal | Direction | What it is |\n|-----|--------|-----------|------------|\n| `motorN[0]` | `h_bridge_cntrl[0]` | OUT | H-bridge control line 1 |\n| `motorN[1]` | `h_bridge_cntrl[1]` | OUT | H-bridge control line 2 |\n| `encoderN[0]` | `enc_in[0]` | IN | Encoder channel A |\n| `encoderN[1]` | `enc_in[1]` | IN | Encoder channel B |\n\nSo for motor 0 (rear right steer), on PMOD 1:\n```\nPMOD1 pin 1  →  H12  →  motor0[0]  →  h_bridge_cntrl[0]  (PWM output)\nPMOD1 pin 5  →  B10  →  motor0[1]  →  h_bridge_cntrl[1]  (PWM output, complementary)\nPMOD1 pin 2  →  E10  →  encoder0[0] →  enc_in[0]          (encoder A)\nPMOD1 pin 6  →  E12  →  encoder0[1] →  enc_in[1]          (encoder B)\n```\n\n---\n\n## The rover layout\n\nThe constraints comments reveal the full motor map — it's a 6-wheel rover with steer + drive on each corner, plus middle wheels:\n\n| Motors | Location | Type |\n|--------|----------|------|\n| 0, 1 | Rear right | Steer, Drive |\n| 2, 3 | Front right | Steer, Drive |\n| 4, 5 | Front left | Steer, Drive |\n| 6, 7 | Rear left | Steer, Drive |\n| 8, 9 | Middle left, Middle right | Drive only |\n| 10–13 | (extra/unused labeled) | — |\n\nMotors 0–7 are on PMOD connectors 1–4. Motors 8–13 are on the Raspberry Pi GPIO header on the Kria board.\n\n---\n\n## What the H-bridge chip sees\n\nThe H-bridge chip (on the PCB) takes those two FPGA output pins and uses them to drive the motor coils with full voltage. The FPGA itself only outputs 3.3V logic — the H-bridge amplifies that to whatever the motor supply voltage is. The two-pin scheme from the `H_Bridge_Driver` means:\n\n- Forward: `out1` carries the PWM, `out2` is held high\n- Reverse: `out2` carries the PWM, `out1` is held high\n- Stopped (`en=0`): both pins go low → H-bridge coasts/brakes\n\nThe encoder signals go the other direction — the encoder on the motor shaft outputs 3.3V quadrature pulses back into the FPGA pins, which the `quadDecoder` reads.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> are the 2 remaining pins (because there are 6) a ground and src",
    "Yes, exactly. The FPGA/PMOD connectors follow a standard pinout where the remaining 2 pins of each 6-pin group are **GND** and **VCC (3.3V)**. They're not signal pins so they don't appear in the constraints file at all — Vivado only needs to know about the programmable signal pins.\n\nFor a standard PMOD connector the 6-pin layout is:\n\n```\nPin 1: Signal (motor[0] or encoder[0])\nPin 2: Signal (motor[1] or encoder[1])  ← wait, that's 4 signals across upper+lower\nPin 3: GND\nPin 4: VCC (3.3V)\n```\n\nActually for the Kria's PMOD specifically, each PMOD has **12 pins total** (upper row + lower row of 6), where each row of 6 is:\n\n```\n[ sig ][ sig ][ sig ][ sig ][ GND ][ VCC ]\n```\n\nSo the 4 signal pins per motor (2 motor + 2 encoder) use 4 of those signal slots, and the remaining 2 in that row are GND and VCC — power and ground reference for the connected PCB/H-bridge circuit. That's the standard PMOD spec.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> are there different blocks for the steering servos versus normal servos",
    "Looking at the constraints, the steering motors (e.g., motor0 = \"rear right steer\") use the same `motor_controller` block as the drive wheels — they're all DC motors with encoders, not servos.\n\nBut let me check the rover software side since there were separate servo files there.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "No, there's no separate FPGA block for steering. Here's the distinction:\n\n**In the FPGA (hardware):** All 14 motors use the identical `motor_controller` block — same PWM + H-bridge driver + quadrature decoder. The hardware doesn't know or care whether a motor is steering or driving.\n\n**In the software (C code):** There's a layered abstraction:\n\n- `MotorController` — raw MMIO wrapper, talks directly to the FPGA registers\n- `Servo` — wraps a `MotorController` + a `PIDController`. This is what makes a DC motor *behave* like a positional servo: it reads the encoder count and runs a PID loop to drive the motor to a target position.\n- `steering_motor_t` — wraps a `Servo` and adds calibration state machine logic (finding left/right/center limits) so the steering angle can be commanded in meaningful units.\n\nSo \"servo\" here doesn't mean a hobby RC servo — it means a DC motor being position-controlled via PID in software. The FPGA just provides raw PWM + encoder counting; all the closed-loop control happens on the ARM side.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> can you explain the pid loop, and is that only in software?",
    "Let me read the PID code first.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Yes, the PID is entirely in software. Here's how it works:\n\n---\n\n## The PID loop\n\nA PID controller tries to drive a measured value to a target (setpoint) by computing three terms and summing them into an output:\n\n**Proportional** — output proportional to current error. If you're far from the target, push hard; if you're close, push gently.\n```\nP = Kp * error          (Kp = 15.0)\n```\n\n**Integral** — accumulates past error over time. Corrects for steady-state offset where P alone isn't enough to reach the target (e.g. friction). Uses trapezoidal integration (averages current and previous error) for better accuracy than simple Euler:\n```\nI += 0.5 * Ki * dt * (error + prevError)    (Ki = 30.0)\n```\nThe integrator is clamped to ±20 to prevent **windup** — where the integrator accumulates a huge value while the motor is stalled, then overshoots badly when it finally moves.\n\n**Derivative** — reacts to how fast the error is changing, damping oscillation. Critically, it's computed on the **measurement** rather than the error, which avoids a spike when the setpoint suddenly changes (\"derivative kick\"):\n```\nD = f(Kd, measurement - prevMeasurement, tau)    (Kd = 2.0)\n```\nThe `tau` parameter (0.04) is a low-pass filter time constant that smooths out noise on the derivative term — raw encoder counts are noisy and an unfiltered derivative would be jittery.\n\nThe final output is clamped to **±255**, which maps directly to the 8-bit duty cycle the FPGA expects.\n\n---\n\n## How it connects to the hardware\n\n`Servo_update()` is called repeatedly (sample time = 1ms) and does:\n\n1. Read `motor_pos` from the FPGA quadrature decoder → current position in encoder counts\n2. Call `PIDController_update(setpoint, counts)` → get output in range ±255\n3. Sign of output → set `motor_dir` bit in control vector\n4. Magnitude of output → set `duty_cycle` byte in control vector\n5. Write the new control vector to the FPGA GPIO register → FPGA immediately updates PWM\n\nSo the loop is: **encoder counts (FPGA) → PID math (ARM) → PWM duty + direction (FPGA)**. The FPGA handles the high-frequency PWM generation; the ARM handles the control logic at 1kHz.\n\n---\n\n## Why only in software?\n\nThere's no hardware PID here because the Kria's ARM cores are fast enough (1GHz+) to run 14 PID loops at 1kHz easily, and keeping it in software makes the gains (`Kp`, `Ki`, `Kd`) trivially tunable without re-synthesizing the FPGA bitstream. A hardware PID in the PL would only be necessary if you needed sub-microsecond loop rates, which motor position control doesn't require.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> what does h bridge mean",
    "An H-bridge is a circuit that lets you drive current through a motor in either direction using 4 switches arranged in the shape of the letter \"H\":\n\n```\nVCC\n |\n[S1]       [S2]\n |           |\n +---[MOTOR]-+\n |           |\n[S3]       [S4]\n |\nGND\n```\n\nTo spin **forward**, close S1 and S4 (current flows left→right through motor):\n```\nVCC\n |\n[ON ]       [OFF]\n |           \n +---[MOTOR]-+\n             |\n[OFF]       [ON ]\n             |\n            GND\n```\n\nTo spin **reverse**, close S2 and S3 (current flows right→left):\n```\nVCC\n         |\n[OFF]   [ON ]\n         |\n +---[MOTOR]-+\n |\n[ON ]   [OFF]\n |\nGND\n```\n\nThe key insight is that the motor supply voltage (could be 12V, 24V, whatever the motors need) is completely separate from the FPGA's 3.3V logic. The FPGA's two output pins just switch the transistors on/off — the H-bridge chip does the actual high-current, high-voltage work.\n\nClosing S1+S3 or S2+S4 simultaneously would short VCC directly to GND — that's a shoot-through fault and would destroy the chip. The `H_Bridge_Driver` logic in the FPGA is designed so `out1` and `out2` are never both high at the same time, which prevents this.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> if there are only 2 physical pins controlling this, how does it work since it looks like there are 4 things",
    "The H-bridge chip on the PCB handles that internally. The 4 switches aren't controlled independently — they're paired:\n\n- S1 and S4 are always switched together (call it \"side A\")\n- S2 and S3 are always switched together (call it \"side B\")\n\nSo the chip only needs 2 input pins to control all 4 switches:\n\n```\nout1 → controls S1 + S4 together\nout2 → controls S2 + S3 together\n```\n\nThe chip's internal logic ensures that when one side turns on, the other turns off (with a small dead-time to prevent shoot-through). You never need to control all 4 switches independently for a simple DC motor — the pairing is fixed by physics of what you're trying to do.\n\nSo the FPGA's 2 pins map cleanly:\n- `out1` high, `out2` low → forward\n- `out1` low, `out2` high → reverse  \n- both low → motor coasts/brakes\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> where are these switches though?",
    "They're transistors inside the H-bridge chip on the PCB. Let me check what chip is actually used.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "The PCB schematic is a binary/compressed format — I can't read the chip name from it directly. But based on the constraints and the rest of the codebase, I can give you a definitive answer without it.\n\n---\n\nYes, the switches are transistors — specifically **MOSFETs** inside a dedicated H-bridge driver IC on the PCB. The exact chip isn't readable from the binary schematic file, but common choices for rover-scale motors are chips like the DRV8833, DRV8871, or TB6612. They all work the same way internally:\n\n```\n         VCC (motor supply, e.g. 12V)\n          |\n    ┌─────┴─────┐\n   [Q1 MOSFET] [Q2 MOSFET]   ← high-side switches (P-type or N-type with bootstrap)\n    |           |\n    +───[MOTOR]─+\n    |           |\n   [Q3 MOSFET] [Q4 MOSFET]   ← low-side switches (N-type)\n    └─────┬─────┘\n         GND\n```\n\nA MOSFET acts as a switch: apply a small voltage to its gate pin → it turns on and conducts current between its drain and source. No gate voltage → it's off. The H-bridge chip's internal logic takes your two FPGA input pins and drives the gates of all four MOSFETs appropriately, including enforcing the dead-time (a tiny delay when switching direction so Q1 and Q3 are never on simultaneously, which would short VCC to GND).\n\nSo the full chain is:\n\n```\nARM writes duty/dir → FPGA generates 3.3V logic on 2 pins → H-bridge chip gates 4 MOSFETs → motor sees full supply voltage\n```\n\nThe FPGA never touches the motor supply voltage at all — it just controls the gates.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> in light of this, what is on the 4 pins that go from the pcb to the motors",
    "The 4 pins going from the PCB to each motor are:\n\n**2 pins out → motor power**\nThese carry the actual motor supply voltage (e.g. 12V) switched by the MOSFETs. The H-bridge drives these two wires with full current — this is what actually spins the motor. By alternating which wire is high/low, direction is controlled. The PWM duty cycle is achieved by rapidly switching the MOSFETs on and off.\n\n**2 pins in → encoder**\nThese carry the quadrature encoder signals back from the motor. The encoder is a small sensor (usually optical or magnetic) built into the motor that outputs two 3.3V square waves as the shaft rotates. These go back to the FPGA pins for position counting.\n\nSo the split is: 2 wires deliver power to the motor, 2 wires read position back from it. The FPGA's `motor[0]` and `motor[1]` signals never connect to the motor directly — they only go as far as the H-bridge chip on the PCB, which then drives the actual motor wires with high current.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> and then those encoder values make it back to the fpga i assume?",
    "Yes, exactly. The full round-trip for one motor is:\n\n```\nFPGA                    PCB                      Motor\n────                    ───                      ─────\nmotor[0] ──────────► H-bridge ──── wire A ────► motor coil\nmotor[1] ──────────► H-bridge ──── wire B ────► motor coil\n\nencoder[0] ◄──────────────────── enc A ◄─────── encoder chip\nencoder[1] ◄──────────────────── enc B ◄─────── encoder chip\n```\n\nThe encoder signals come straight back into the FPGA pins defined in the constraints file (e.g. `encoder0[0]` and `encoder0[1]`), which wire directly into `enc_in[0]` and `enc_in[1]` on the `motor_controller` block, which feeds the `quadDecoder`, which updates the 16-bit position counter, which the ARM reads back over AXI to close the PID loop.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> what does the zynq ultrascale thing do?",
    "The Zynq UltraScale+ is the main chip on the Kria board — it's the brain of the whole system. What makes it unusual is that it's **two things in one package**:\n\n**Processing System (PS) — the ARM side**\nA quad-core ARM Cortex-A53 running at ~1.3GHz. This is a full CPU that boots Linux, runs your C rover code, handles networking, and talks to the FPGA side over an internal bus. All the PID loops, the control server, the IMU filtering (ESKF) — that all runs here.\n\n**Programmable Logic (PL) — the FPGA side**\nA sea of configurable logic gates that you program with Vivado. This is where all the Verilog you've been looking at lives — the 14 motor controllers, PWM generators, quadrature decoders, watchdog, etc. It runs at hardware speed (100MHz+), handling the timing-critical stuff that a CPU can't do reliably, like generating precise PWM signals and counting encoder pulses without missing any.\n\n**The key thing** is that the PS and PL are on the same chip and connected by a high-speed internal AXI bus. So when your C code does a memory-mapped write to a GPIO register, that signal crosses from the ARM into the FPGA fabric in nanoseconds — no external bus, no latency. That's why this architecture works well for motor control: the CPU handles the intelligence, the FPGA handles the real-time hardware interface, and they're tightly coupled.\n\nThe alternative would be a separate microcontroller talking to a separate FPGA over SPI or UART, which adds latency and complexity. The Zynq puts it all in one chip.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> is the zynq the same as the SoM",
    "Close but not exactly the same thing — they're related but at different levels:\n\n**Zynq UltraScale+** is the silicon chip itself (the `xck26` you can see in the `.bd` file). Just the die.\n\n**SoM (System on Module)** is the Kria K26 — a small board that packages the Zynq chip together with RAM, flash, power regulators, and other supporting components into a compact module. The SoM is what you physically plug into the carrier board.\n\n**Kria KV260** (or KR260) is the carrier board that the SoM plugs into, which breaks out all the pins to connectors — the PMODs, the Raspberry Pi header, Ethernet, etc.\n\nSo the hierarchy is:\n```\nZynq UltraScale+ xck26   ← the chip\n    └── inside Kria K26 SoM   ← the module\n            └── plugged into KV260/KR260 carrier board   ← the full board\n```\n\nWhen people say \"the Kria\" they usually mean the whole thing. When Vivado says `xck26` it's referring specifically to the Zynq chip inside the SoM.\n[Tool uses: none]",
